SIMPLE: necessary
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Necessary
<hw>Nec"es*sa*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>necessarius</ets>, from <ets>necesse</ets> unavoidable, necessary;
of uncertain origin: cf. F. <ets>n⟦eacute⟧cessaire</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Such as must be; impossible to be otherwise; not to be
avoided; inevitable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Death, a <qex>necessary</qex> end,⟦br⟧
Will come when it will come.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Impossible to be otherwise, or to be dispensed with,
without preventing the attainment of a desired result; indispensable;
requisite; essential.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧'T is <xex>necessary</xex> he should
die.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A certain kind of temper is <qex>necessary</qex> to the pleasure
and quiet of our minds.</q> <rj><qau>Tillotson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Acting from necessity or compulsion; involuntary; --
opposed to <ant>free</ant>; <as>as, whether man is a <ex>necessary</ex>
or a free agent is a question much discussed</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Necessary</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Necessary
<hw>Nec"es*sa*ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Necessaries</plw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.</plu> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A thing
that is necessary or indispensable to some purpose; something that one
can not do without; a requisite; an essential; -- used chiefly in the
plural; <as>as, the <ex>necessaries</ex> of life</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A privy; a water-closet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Such things, in
respect to infants, lunatics, and married women, as are requisite for
support suitable to station.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Necessitarian</ent>⟦br⟧
